<styl>by <m0>By INA PAIVA CORDLE<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Business Writer<ep>
   In the first collaboration between two of South Florida's most seasoned developers, Michael Swerdlow plans to build a retail and entertainment center at Armando Codina's giant planned industrial complex in West Dade.<ep>
   Swerdlow said Monday that he plans to buy a 90-acre parcel at the south end of Codina's proposed Beacon TradePort at the intersection of the turnpike and State Road 836, just west of Miami International Mall. Neither he nor Armando Codina, chief executive of the Codina Group, would disclose the purchase price, but Swerdlow is buying about one-fourth of a 373-acre parcel said to cost a total of more than $25 million.<ep>
   The deal is expected to close in about six to eight months, simultaneously with Codina's purchase of the entire property from a Chinese investment group. The land, under contract since November, is now in the permitting and planning stages. Zoned agricultural, it has been used for cattle grazing.<ep>
   Beacon TradePort will be Codina's largest and most ambitious project to date, with than 250 acres of high-end warehouses.<ep>
   The retail and entertainment component, called Dolphin Center at Beacon TradePort, will most likely take the form of an enclosed mall, said Swerdlow, chairman of the Michael Swerdlow Co. Expected to open in two years, the center will have 24 movie screens, stores and restaurants, with ``an entertainment area for families with small children and another area devoted to grown-ups,'' he said.<ep>
   ''We're hoping to make it a real regional draw,'' Swerdlow said, citing the complex's excellent location and access to major roads.<ep>
   ''I think there's no better location in South Florida than this one,'' he said. ``That's where the population is moving, and there's tremendous tourist potential from the airport and seaport. If they can get to Sawgrass Mills, they can certainly <m2><ql>
